{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496477"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:48:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:48:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1366"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1366"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.09,0.57,0.17,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89114"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1366"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73319"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"952"},{"type":"tags","id":"2139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42295"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89114"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns regarding his nails. He reports that this condition has gradually developed over the course of several months and affects a number of his fingernails. His nails are not particularly itchy or painful. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He reports that he is a vegetarian. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Inspection of his nails reveals thickening and distal separation of the nail plate from the nail bed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subungual melanoma","Onychogryphosis","Onychomycosis","Koilonychia","Psoriatic nail changes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows nail thickening (hyperkeratosis) and distal onycholysis, which are classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Eonychomycosis\u003C/strong\u003E. Onychomycosis is a chronic fungal nail infection that can affect both fingernails and toenails. It is most commonly caused by dermatophytes, particularly \u003Cem\u003ETrichophyton rubrum\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003ET. interdigitale\u003C/em\u003E, but can also be caused by yeasts such as \u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E or molds. The condition typically develops gradually over months, as seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubungual melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents as a pigmented band in the nail that becomes wider over time. It would be an unlikely diagnosis given the multiple nail involvement and lack of pigmentation described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnychogryphosis\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as ram\u0027s horn nails, is characterised by generalised thickening of the nail with elongation and often increased curvature. This condition typically affects toenails, particularly in older individuals, and would not match the description provided for this young patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKoilonychia\u003C/strong\u003E refers to spoon-shaped nails, which are often associated with iron deficiency anaemia. While the patient is a vegetarian, which could potentially lead to iron deficiency, the nail changes described do not match koilonychia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriatic nail changes\u003C/strong\u003E can include pitting, onycholysis, and subungual hyperkeratosis. However, it would be rare to have psoriatic nail changes without other signs of chronic plaque psoriasis or psoriatic arthritis, which are not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnychomycosis is a difficult-to-treat condition that often requires prolonged courses of oral antifungal therapy. Diagnosis is typically confirmed by microscopy and culture of nail clippings. Treatment options include oral terbinafine or itraconazole, often for several months, depending on the extent of nail involvement and the causative organism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oonychomycosis is a chronic fungal nail infection characterised by nail thickening, discolouration, and distal onycholysis.","Dermatophytes, particularly Trichophyton species, are the most common causative agents of onychomycosis.","Onychomycosis often requires prolonged oral antifungal therapy for effective treatment."],"references":["Tully AS, Trayes KP, Studdiford JS. Evaluation of nail abnormalities. Am Fam Physician. 2012 Apr 15;85(8):779-87. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2012/0415/p779.html","Onychomycosis. In: eTG complete [Online]. 2015. [updated 2019 Jun; cited 2021 Feb 20]. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/","Fungal nail infections. In: Dermnet NZ [Online]. 2003 [updated 2003; cited 2020 Feb 20]. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/fungal-nail-infections/","Melanoma of the nail unit. In: Dermnet NZ [Online]. 2011 [updated 2011; cited 2020 Feb 120]. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/melanoma-of-nail-unit/","Onychogryphosis. In: Dermnet NZ [Online]. 2019 [updated 2019 Sep; cited 2020 Feb 20]. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/onychogryphosis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73319"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1366"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20053"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20053"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1a76f733-c8cc-4325-9b02-6b3449abcbc1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1a76f733-c8cc-4325-9b02-6b3449abcbc1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":410}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/73319"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-07T18:46:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-07T18:53:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1366"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89114"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":nu